I. Introduction

In this project, we fit a forecasting model with trend, seasonal dummies, and cycles. The data we use is the stock price of Bitcoin, which is an innovative payment network and a new kind of money. Bitcoin is a very high-risk investment because it’s a volatile asset. That means that Bitcoin values may rise or fall dramatically in value over a very short period—even as quickly as a few hours or days. The Bitcoin network of miners makes money from Bitcoin by successfully validating blocks and being rewarded. The dataset includes the daily stock price (Open, High, Low, Close, Adj Close, Volume) from Sep.17th 2014 to May.5th 2022.

II. Results

  1. Produce a time-series plot of your data including the respective ACF and PACF plots.
BTC <- read_csv("BTC-USD.csv")
## Rows: 2788 Columns: 7

BTC_ts = ts(BTC$`Adj Close`, start=2014.71, freq=365)
plot(BTC_ts, main = "Bitcoin stock price from 2014-2022", ylab="Price")

acf(BTC_ts, main="ACF of Bitcoin stock price from 2014-2022")

pacf(BTC_ts, main="PACF of Bitcoin stock price from 2014-2022")

The time series plot has a clear upward trend and is not covariance stationary. The stock price is lowest at the beginning and reaches its peak in around the end of 2021. We still need to analyze in details to see if seasonality and cycles exist. Moreover, ACF slowly decays (to 0) and there is one spike for PACF, suggesting maybe an AR(1) model.

  1. Plot the stl decomposition plot of your data, and discuss the results.
BTC_ts %>% stl(t.window=13, s.window="periodic", robust=TRUE) %>% autoplot()

We can see trend since the trend component slowly increases from 2014 to 2020, increases faster and reaches the spikes after 2020, and decreases at the end of 2021. There are also strong seasonal components because the pattern shows that the stock price increases at the beginning of the year, decreases strongly later, then gradually increases with some minor decreases. The remainder is quite stable at first, but fluctuates around 2018. Starting from 2021, the remainder becomes very volatile and suggests that some cycles present.

  1. Fit a model that includes, trend, seasonality and cyclical components. Make sure to discuss your model in detail.
# Additive decomposition
dcmp = decompose(ts(BTC_ts, frequency=365), "additive")
plot(dcmp)

# Our first model
fit <- tslm(BTC_ts ~ dcmp$trend + dcmp$season)
summary(fit)

We first do an additive decomposition, and it shows mostly similar results from the stl decomposition in (b), except that the seasonal component here is more ragged. The trend plot is more smooth and the trend does not show the huge fluctuations between 2020 to 2022. The trend only captures one drop at the end.

We use a linear regression plus the trend and seasonality in the additive decomposition as our first model. We can see that the p value of the intercept and the two predictors, dcmp$trend and dcmp$season, are both very small, meaning that the two predictors are statistically significant. The \(R^2\) of 0.8915 also shows that the model captures most data in the set and performs pretty well. The F-statistics of the model is significant as well because the p-value is very small. Therefore, the model is a valid model.

  1. Plot the respective residuals vs. fitted values and discuss your observations.
t <- seq(2014, 2023, length=length(BTC_ts))
plot(t, fit$residuals, main="Residuals vs. fitted values", 
     ylab="Residuals", type='l', xlab="Fitted Values")
abline(0,0)

Residuals show a yearly cyclic pattern that is very obvious from 2014 to 2021. There is a small peak at the end of 2017, and the residuals after 2021 become larger in absolute value. This shows that our model does not capture the fluctuations after 2021 very well when there was a huge increase in stock price at that time because of the crypto exchange trend that happened at that time.

  1. Plot the ACF and PACF of the respective residuals and interpret the plots.
tsdisplay(fit$residuals)

tsdisplay(fit$residuals, lag.max = 20)

We see that ACF slowly decays to 0 and there is one significant spike in PACF, suggesting there might be an AR(1) present in residuals.

  1. Plot the respective CUSUM and interpret the plot.
plot(efp(fit$residuals ~ 1, type="Rec-CUSUM"))

The CUSUM chart plots the cumulative sums of the deviations of the sample values from a target value. A segment of the CUSUM chart with an upward slope indicates a period where the values tend to be above average. Likewise, a segment with a downward slope indicates a period of time where the values tend to be below the average. Our CUSUM plot shows that there is some structural change in our residuals, as they surpass the red lines.

  1. For your model, discuss the associated diagnostic statistics.

All statistics show that there are some data changes after 2021 that our model did not capture completely. These lead to the increase, structural changes, and potential patterns in our residuals. However, our model does pretty much capture the seasonality and especially everything before 2020. This is also helpful because cyclic patterns suggest that these patterns may repeat in the future when there are fewer unexpected events like Covid.

The mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) is a measure of prediction accuracy of a forecasting method in statistics. A MAPE less than 5% is considered as an indication that the forecast is acceptably accurate. The MAPE of the ARIMA model is 2.887295, and the MAPE of our first model is 1.205276. Therefore, our first model performs better in terms of MAPE.

We want to see the relationship between stock price and the volume, or the number of tradings. We can also see an increase in volume as a good sign for the stock price. From the time series plot, we see that there is a really strong spike in 2021, which corresponds to the increase in stock price at that time. The volume is generally stable apart from around that spike. From the ACF and PACF plots, we can also see that they are similar to those of stock price, where we can probably hold an AR model.

From our VAR model, we see that volume is dependent on past values of stock price and past values of itself, which makes sense because the stock price increases then more people get into the market to trade. The volume does not depend on lag 1 of stock price very much, which is also reasonable, since they happen at the same time. Moreover, stock price depends on its lagged value (l1) and lagged values of volume (l2 and l3). This also makes sense as the change in volume usually does not affect stock price instantaneously, but they do drive up the future stock prices if they increase. The residual plots show that there might be cycles presented, but they are more complex (i.e., we cannot spot the trend right away), so overall our VAR model fits most data.

Impulse response functions trace the dynamic impact to a system of a “shock” or change to an input. The impulse response functions show similar results of our interpretation before. For example, an increase in volume will drive up the stock price slowly, and a change in stock price has a more immediate effect on volume.

  1. Perform a Granger-Causality test on your variables and discuss your results from the test.
grangertest(BTC_ts ~ volume_ts, order=3)

The Granger causality test is a statistical hypothesis test for determining whether one time series is useful in forecasting another. The results of the test show that there are strong relationship between the two variables because the p value is less than 0.05 and statistically significant. So we can use one variable to forecast another.

III. Conclusions and Future Work

In conclusion, we identified strengths and weaknesses in our different models, including our first linear regression that uses the trend and seasonality from additive components, an AR(1) model, a combination of our first model and the AR(1) model, and finally the VAR model. We recognized that we have captured the data before 2020 quite well, but we fail to capture some patterns, especially in the residuals, after 2020. This is due to changes in economic activities and other events, including the crypto exchange trends and especially Covid, causing a bit of economic depression. We also realized that a combination of our linear regression and AR(1) model would be the best for forecasting in terms of MAPE. Moreover, in constructing a VAR model, we tested and confirmed a strong relationship between the stock price and volume. This implies that every model of us has captured some information that is different from other models. In the future, we will consider a combination of all of the models to capture more information in the data. Furthermore, to compare our forecasting with the actual stock prices in 2022, we found out that our forecast is generally a bit higher. Therefore, in the future, we will consider some other factors, such as Elon Musk’s economic prediction, which influenced Bitcoin’s stock price significantly in the past.
